/i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). See also   Wallis  .","habitational name from Wales, the country named from Old English <i>wēalas</i> ‘foreigners’ (especially those speaking Celtic or Romance languages). This meaning of the surname is quite rare."],"variants":[{"name":"Wailes","meanings":["English: variant of   Wales  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]}]},{"name":"Cyfan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Zbigniew, Andrzej, Jerzy, Krystyna.","Polish: from a derivative of <i>cyranka</i> ‘teal’, hence a nickname for someone thought to resemble the bird in some way."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"wife Cyfan of Wales married Cyfan of Wales before 1055, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1040–1055":"1040–1055","1055–1095":"1055–1095","–Female":"Surnud","before 1055":"enne 1055","1055":"1055","1095":"1095","1040":"1040","Europe":"Europe","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1040–1055":"1